    "response": "Step 1: Let \\(d = \\gcd(a, b)\\). Write \\(a = d x\\), \\(b = d y\\) with \\(\\gcd(x, y) = 1\\). Then \\(\\operatorname{lcm}(a, b) = d x y\\). The given equation \\(ab = \\left(\\frac{\\operatorname{lcm}(a, b)}{\\gcd(a, b)}\\right)^2\\) becomes \\(d^2 x y = (x y)^2\\), so \\(d^2 = x y\\).\n\nStep 2: Since \\(x\\) and \\(y\\) are coprime and their product is a perfect square, each must be a perfect square. Write \\(x = u^2\\), \\(y = v^2\\) with \\(\\gcd(u, v) = 1\\). Then \\(d = u v\\), so \\(a = u^3 v\\) and \\(b = u v^3\\).\n\nStep 3: Both \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) must not exceed 100, so \\(u^3 v \\le 100\\) and \\(u v^3 \\le 100\\). Also \\(u, v\\) are positive integers with \\(\\gcd(u, v) = 1\\).\n\nStep 4: From \\(u^3 \\le 100\\), we have \\(u \\le 4\\). For each \\(u\\) from 1 to 4, find \\(v\\) satisfying both inequalities and coprimality:\n- \\(u = 1\\): \\(v^3 \\le 100\\) gives \\(v \\le 4\\), and \\(\\gcd(1, v)=1\\) always. So \\(v = 1, 2, 3, 4\\).\n- \\(u = 2\\): \\(8v \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v \\le 12\\); \\(2v^3 \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v^3 \\le 50 \\Rightarrow v \\le 3\\). \\(\\gcd(2, v)=1\\) requires \\(v\\) odd, so \\(v = 1, 3\\).\n- \\(u = 3\\): \\(27v \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v \\le 3\\); \\(3v^3 \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v^3 \\le 33.3 \\Rightarrow v \\le 3\\). \\(\\gcd(3, v)=1\\) requires \\(v\\) not multiple of 3, so \\(v = 1, 2\\).\n- \\(u = 4\\): \\(64v \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v = 1\\); \\(4v^3 \\le 100 \\Rightarrow v^3 \\le 25 \\Rightarrow v \\le 2\\), but \\(v=1\\) only satisfies the first bound. \\(\\gcd(4, 1)=1\\), so \\(v = 1\\).\n\nStep 5: Compute \\(a+b = u v (u^2 + v^2)\\) for each valid pair:\n- \\((1,1)\\): \\(1\\cdot1\\cdot(1+1)=2\\)\n- \\((1,2)\\): \\(1\\cdot2\\cdot(1+4)=10\\)\n- \\((1,3)\\): \\(1\\cdot3\\cdot(1+9)=30\\)\n- \\((1,4)\\): \\(1\\cdot4\\cdot(1+16)=68\\)\n- \\((2,1)\\): same as \\((1,2)\\): 10\n- \\((2,3)\\): \\(2\\cdot3\\cdot(4+9)=6\\cdot13=78\\)\n- \\((3,1)\\): same as \\((1,3)\\): 30\n- \\((3,2)\\): same as \\((2,3)\\): 78\n- \\((4,1)\\): same as \\((1,4)\\): 68\n\nStep 6: The largest sum is 78.\n\nFinal Answer: 78",
