    "response": "We are given a system of equations for real numbers \\(a_1, a_2, \\dots, a_{2005}\\):  \n\\[\n\\sum_{i=1}^{2005} a_i i^k = 0 \\quad\\text{for } k=1,2,\\dots,2004,\\qquad \n\\sum_{i=1}^{2005} a_i i^{2005} = 1.\n\\]  \nDefine the linear functional \\(L(f) = \\sum_{i=1}^{2005} a_i f(i)\\) on polynomials. Then \\(L(x^k)=0\\) for \\(k=1,\\dots,2004\\) and \\(L(x^{2005})=1\\).\n\nConsider the polynomial \\(Q(x) = \\prod_{j=1}^{2005}(x-j)\\). Since \\(Q(i)=0\\) for all \\(i=1,\\dots,2005\\), we have \\(L(Q)=0\\). Expand \\(Q(x)=x^{2005}+c_{2004}x^{2004}+\\cdots+c_1x+c_0\\). Then  \n\\[\nL(Q)=L(x^{2005})+c_{2004}L(x^{2004})+\\cdots+c_1L(x)+c_0L(1)=1+0+\\cdots+0+c_0L(1)=0,\n\\]  \nso \\(L(1) = -1/c_0\\). Compute \\(c_0=Q(0)=\\prod_{j=1}^{2005}(-j)=(-1)^{2005}\\,2005! = -2005!\\). Hence  \n\\[\nL(1) = -\\frac{1}{-2005!} = \\frac{1}{2005!}.\n\\]\n\nThe Lagrange basis polynomial that is \\(1\\) at \\(x=1\\) and \\(0\\) at \\(x=2,\\dots,2005\\) is  \n\\[\n\\ell_1(x)=\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}\\frac{x-j}{1-j}.\n\\]  \nIts degree is \\(2004\\), so when we write \\(\\ell_1(x)=\\sum_{k=0}^{2004}b_kx^k\\), we have \\(L(\\ell_1)=b_0L(1)+\\sum_{k=1}^{2004}b_kL(x^k)=b_0L(1)\\) because \\(L(x^k)=0\\) for \\(k\\ge1\\). The constant term is  \n\\[\nb_0=\\ell_1(0)=\\frac{\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}(-j)}{\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}(1-j)}.\n\\]  \nThe numerator is \\((-1)^{2004}\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}j = 2005!\\). The denominator is \\(\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}(1-j)=\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}(-(j-1))=(-1)^{2004}\\prod_{j=2}^{2005}(j-1)=\\prod_{i=1}^{2004}i=2004!\\). Thus \\(b_0=2005!/2004! = 2005\\).\n\nSince \\(a_1 = L(\\ell_1)\\) (because \\(\\ell_1(i)=1\\) only for \\(i=1\\)), we obtain  \n\\[\na_1 = b_0L(1) = 2005\\cdot\\frac{1}{2005!} = \\frac{2005}{2005!} = \\frac{1}{2004!}.\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{1}{2004!}}\n\\]",
